body:
Okay. I think I'm starting to understand. It seems there is no `keyboard_manager` instance being passed to `dialog.modal`. According to the documentation, modal can receive a `keyboard_manager` property, but look at the file `about.js` as an example:

abous.js:25

```
    dialog.modal({
        title: 'About IPython Notebook',
        body: body,
        buttons: { 'OK': {} }
    });
```

Initially I thought that `edit_metadata` was doing things differently (in notebook.js:383), however, I'm not sure because now I see that every dialog object consists of `edit_metadata`, `modal` and `kernel_modal`.
If you test the "Edit Notebook Metadata" option in the notebook, that works correctly. The modal is dismissed after pressing enter and the keyboard is disabled. So maybe we need to add the instance of `keyboard_manager` as an option in `dialog.modal`. What is the difference between creating a modal using `dialog.edit_metadata` and using `dialog.modal`? This is the code that confused me:

```
/**
 * Display a dialog that allows the user to edit the Notebook's metadata.
 */
Notebook.prototype.edit_metadata = function () {
    var that = this;
    dialog.edit_metadata({
        md: this.metadata, 
        callback: function (md) {
            that.metadata = md;
        },
        name: 'Notebook',
        notebook: this,
        keyboard_manager: this.keyboard_manager});
};
```

I was able to find the solution for a couple of modals.

In `about.js`, I added the keyboard manager to `dialog.model`:

```
dialog.modal({
         title: 'About IPython Notebook',
         body: body,
         buttons: { 'OK': {} },
         notebook: IPython.notebook,
         keyboard_manager: IPython.keyboard_manager,
     });
```

I'm not sure if you prefer to use the IPython object in some other way, but since this is for testing purposes, I guess it is okay.

In `quickhelp.js`, there is an issue with this method:

```
 QuickHelp.prototype.show_keyboard_shortcuts = function () {
         /**
         * toggles display of keyboard shortcut dialog
         */
         var that = this;
         if ( this.force_rebuild ) {
             this.shortcut_dialog.remove();
             delete(this.shortcut_dialog);
             this.force_rebuild = false;
         }
```

I don't think `this.force_build` is being defined, so that part never runs. That code is supposed to clean the previous modal and in this case, it refreshes the values for the keyboard manager. I included the property in the constructor:

```
var QuickHelp = function (options) {
    /**
     * Constructor
     *
     * Parameters:
     *  options: dictionary
     *      Dictionary of keyword arguments.
     *          events: $(Events) instance
     *          keyboard_manager: KeyboardManager instance
     *          notebook: Notebook instance
     */
    this.keyboard_manager = options.keyboard_manager;
    this.notebook = options.notebook;
    this.keyboard_manager.quick_help = this;
    this.events = options.events;
    this.force_rebuild = false;
};
```

and included the line `this.force_rebuild = true;` at the end of the method.

However, I haven't been able to find what is the problem with the restart button in the toolbar. Interestingly, restarting the kernel using `Kernel->Restart` disables the keyboard manager correctly.

Yes, commenting out `env-notebook.focus_cell();` maintains the keyboard manager disabled but then when the browser reaches this code (dialog.js:93):

```
    modal.on("shown.bs.modal", function() {
        setTimeout(function() {
            footer.find("button").last().focus();
            if (options.open) {
                $.proxy(options.open, modal)();
            }
        }, 0);
```

The keyboard manager is enabled again. Commenting out `focus()` solves the issue but creates many bugs in the process.

I think I figured it out. The problem is in `keyboardmanager.js:190`:

```
KeyboardManager.prototype.register_events = function (e) {
    var that = this;
    var handle_focus = function () {
        that.disable();
    };
    var handle_blur = function () {
        that.enable();
    };
    e.on('focusin', handle_focus);
    e.on('focusout', handle_blur);
```

After you click on any button, the `focusin` event is triggered followed by the `focus` event and finally `focusout` is activated. In our case, we need to keep the property `enabled=false` of the keyboard manager until the modal is dismissed. However, after `focusout`, `handle_blur` sets `enabled=true` and then we are able to change the cells even when the modal is active. Here `register_events` is passing the element `div#maintoolbar-container`, so this applies to the buttons of the toolbar and that's the difference between restarting the kernel from the menu and using the toolbar.

How should we fix this? I suppose disabling keyboard interactions before focus and enabling them again after focus was needed in some special case. Does anyone remember what the issue was that required this behavior?

@takluyver 

> Maybe we should be using register_events on the specific elements that need keyboard interaction instead.

I think that is the best option.

There is another very simple solution. In `toolbar.js:133`:

```
            button.attr('data-jupyter-action', action_name);
            var fun = el.callback|| function(){
                button.blur();
                that.actions.call(action_name)
            };
```

This is forcing `blur();` on the buttons before calling the action (in this case,  `restart_kernel`). The pattern is the following: enabling the keyboard (before modal), disabling the keyboard (when showing the modal), enabling the keyboard (after hiding the modal). Since this change applies to all the buttons of the toolbar, the pattern is the same.

By the way, when you say you have seen a similar issue with dialogs, maybe that is a different problem because modals are supposed to be removed after termination (or equivalently, destroyed after initializing another modal), right?

I don't think `focus_cell()` is enabling the keyboard. It seems to be selecting the cell and applying focus:

notebook.js:712 

```
function () {
    var cell = this.get_selected_cell();
    if (cell === null) {return;}  // No cell is selected
    cell.focus_cell();
 }
```

(`cell.focus_cell()` is simply `this.element.focus();`) That must be the reason why it didn't change anything associated to the keyboard manager when I removed that line (after forcing `.blur();`)

> I remember that for the save button, but for e.g. restart kernel, where it brings up a dialog, we don't want the cell to be focused again.

Uhm, but I believe that is the default behavior in master. I'm assuming `focus();` only selects a cell in command mode.

@Carreau Maybe `env.notebook.focus_cell();` is not needed anymore because I removed it in the restart_kernel action and didn't notice any difference. By the way, I haven't seen issues regarding focus after clicking on a button, but if we need to add `focus_cell()`, that shouldn't be a problem.
